Their Rescue Impossible, Beached Whales Begin to Die Volunteers of the New England Marine Mammal Stranding Network watched helplessly as pilot whales lay dead and dying on Cape Cod Bay's Lieutenant Island in Wellfleet, Mass. Sixty-five whales, some of them 20 feet long and weighing up to a ton, became stranded in a salt marsh Tuesday night. By late yesterday all had died. Robert Prescott, director of the Audubon Society's wildlife sanctuary at Wellfleet Bay, said that, because of size, the whales could not be returned to the water. He said the beaching of a large number of whales on the island ''happens frequently, every 25 years or so.''

Jetliner Lands in Chicago With an Unlisted and Premature Passenger Eun Sook Kim holds her newborn daughter as she is taken to a hospital in Chicago from the Northwest Orient airliner she boarded in Tokyo. Mrs. Kim was not due to be delivered until the end of the month but realized her baby was coming moments before the plane landed at O'Hare Airport. She warned the flight attendants and gave birth to her daughter at her seat. The child, 5 pounds 10 ounces, was fine. So was Mrs. Kim. Her husband, according to an airline agent, ''didn't talk much; he was just perspiring.'' All are now doing well.
